\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces Illustration of a case where immediate HVI and managed final-HV delta assign different quality credit. The neutral rectangles show the hypervolume already contributed by the existing boundary scores $a$ and $c$, while the blue rectangle marks only the additional HVI introduced by candidate $x$. The capped management operator with $N=2$ keeps the boundary scores $a$ and $c$ and removes $x$, so the managed-population hypervolume does not change.}}{35}{figure.caption.13}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:immediate-final-reward-example}{{3.4}{35}{Illustration of a case where immediate HVI and managed final-HV delta assign different quality credit. The neutral rectangles show the hypervolume already contributed by the existing boundary scores $a$ and $c$, while the blue rectangle marks only the additional HVI introduced by candidate $x$. The capped management operator with $N=2$ keeps the boundary scores $a$ and $c$ and removes $x$, so the managed-population hypervolume does not change}{figure.caption.13}{}}
